-- Hong Kong shares slide on weaker financials, gaming sector
-- By Grace Li
-- Tue Jun 17, 2014 04:08AM EDT
-- None



HONG KONG, June 17 (Reuters) - Hong Kong shares finished lower on Tuesday, dragged down by underperforming financial companies and a weaker Macau gaming sector.

The Hang Seng Index <.HSI> closed down 0.4 percent at 23,203.59 points. The China Enterprises Index <.HSCE> of the leading offshore Chinese listings in Hong Kong slumped 0.5 percent. Asia insurer giant AIA Group <1299.HK> shed 1.4 percent, while HSBC Holdings <0005.HK> slipped 0.4 percent. Macau casino shares extended a decline which began in mid-March on fears of weaker growth prospects, with Wynn Macau <1128.HK> down 2.4 percent and MGM China Holdings <2282.HK> off 1.4 percent.  The world's gambling capital said late on Monday it would shorten the permitted transit time stay for Chinese tourists to five days from the current seven days from July 1. [ID:nL4N0OY0YW] Chow Tai Fook Jewellery Group <1929.HK>, the world's largest jewellery retailer, rose 1.3 percent to a 7-week high before its full-year earnings due later on Tuesday.